  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "TG0pxKcZGeUg8MO2/G5ryER7a9A=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\n**Mantaray manifests** are Swarm's native file-collection format \u2014 compacted Merkle tries where each node carries a path segment, a target chunk reference, and metadata, exposing a single root hash that resolves arbitrary paths.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Used for file collections (directories, websites), not our custom document manifests\n- Upload: `POST /bzz` with `Swarm-Collection: true` header + TAR body\n- Download: `GET /bzz/{manifest-hash}/{path}` resolves the path through the trie\n- Supports `indexDocument` (default page) and `errorDocument` (404 page) metadata\n- bee-js: `bee.uploadFile()`, `bee.downloadFile()`, `bee.uploadFiles()`, `bee.uploadCollection()`\n\n## What this unlocks for us\n\n1. **File attachments**: upload images/PDFs via `/bzz`, store the manifest reference inside document ops \u2014 content-addressed and encrypted\n2. **Document export**: package an entire drive as a Swarm collection (HTML + JSON), share via one hash or ENS name\n3. **Static publishing**: deploy the Connect SPA itself to Swarm (HashRouter + ENS = fully decentralized app)\n\n## Why it matters\n\nMantaray is distinct from our app-level `manifest-as-reference` pattern and provides the transport for any file-shaped content. It's also the route to deploying Connect itself on Swarm.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
